SEM images (Fig. 2a, b) show that a large-area Sb2S3 layer is grown on the TiO2 film and consists of the Sb2S3 nanorods that are of a right square prism shape, 50−150 nm in width, ca. 320 nm in length, and a number density (i.e., the number of the different nanorods per unit area) of ca. 36 µm−2 on the TiO2 nanoparticle (ca. 10−20 nm in diameter) film of ca. 110 nm in thickness. Clearly, the Sb2S3 nanorods are grown along the directions out of substrate planes (i.e., out-of-plane growth) with the growth direction tilting some angles from the normal of TiO2 film, resulting in an Sb2S3 nanorod array on the TiO2 film. Fig. 2c shows the transmission electron microscopy (TEM) image of a single Sb2S3 nanorod of ca. 50 nm in width. Both selected area electron diffraction pattern and high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) image (Insets to Fig. 2c) clearly show that the nanorod is single-crystalline in nature and grows along [001] direction, where the HRTEM image exhibits the lattice fringes of 0.35 nm and 0.38 nm in spacing corresponding, respectively, to the 111/1¯1¯1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
